- *19. For each of the inhibitors listed below, describe first their direct
  effect, and then indicate the type of transport mechanism(s) that they block.*

  a. vanadate \
  b. cyanide \
  c. valinomycin

  *Answer:*

  a. *Vanadate:* A phosphate analog that binds to the phosphorylation site of
  P-type ATPases (e.g., $"Na"^+$/$"K"^+$ ATPase, $"Ca"^(2+)$ ATPase) and traps them in the
  phosphorylated E2 state, preventing dephosphorylation and the return
  conformational change. Blocks *primary active transport* mediated by P-type
  ATPases.

  b. *Cyanide:* Binds to cytochrome c oxidase (Complex IV) in the mitochondrial
  electron transport chain, blocking oxidative phosphorylation and ATP
  production. By depleting cellular ATP, cyanide indirectly blocks *all
  energy-dependent transport* (both primary active transport and secondary
  active transport that depends on ion gradients maintained by ATP-driven
  pumps).

  c. *Valinomycin:* A potassium ionophore that binds $"K"^+$ and shuttles it across
  membranes, dissipating the $"K"^+$ concentration gradient and collapsing the
  membrane potential. This disrupts processes that depend on the membrane
  potential and indirectly blocks *secondary active transport* that relies on
  the electrochemical gradient (e.g., $"Na"^+$-coupled symport/antiport), as well
  as any transport affected by membrane depolarization.
